title: MED-SE: Medical Entity Definition-based Sentence Embedding
MED-SE: Medical Entity Definition-based Sentence Embedding
correspondingData: The authors developed the Medical Entity Definition-based Sentence Embedding (MED-SE) due to the underperformance of existing unsupervised contrastive learning techniques in clinical semantic textual similarity tasks. MED-SE is a novel framework that utilizes medical entity definitions to improve the representation of clinical sentences by providing additional knowledge on medical concepts.

correspondingData: Synthetic data created to mimic bill writing intricacies can significantly improve the predictive performance when training with both human-labeled and synthetic data. This is because synthetic data reflects the complex bill writing process and helps the model better understand the relationships among bills. By leveraging semantic similarities between subsections, the model can infer bill linkages, which helps scholars better understand the legislative process.

title: AltUB: Alternating Training Method to Update Base Distribution of Normalizing Flow for Anomaly Detection
correspondingData: The motivation of AltUB is to improve the stability of performance of normalizing flow for anomaly detection. It introduces alternating training to update the base distribution of normalizing flow for anomaly detection, which effectively improves the expressive power of the normalizing flow, especially for anomaly detection.

title: How to Find Your Friendly Neighborhood: Graph Attention Design with Self-Supervision
correspondingData: The authors propose a self-supervised graph attention network (SuperGAT) that utilizes two attention forms to predict edges and improves the performance in distinguishing mislinked neighbors. Their recipe for attention design shows improved performance over baselines in experiments on 17 real-world datasets.

title: How to Find Your Friendly Neighborhood: Graph Attention Design with Self-Supervision
correspondingData: The key contribution of this paper is the proposal of a self-supervised graph attention network called SuperGAT, which uses two attention forms to predict edges and learns more expressive attention in distinguishing mislinked neighbors. The authors provide guidance on which attention design to use based on known factors such as homophily and average degree, and experiments show that the models designed by the proposed method outperform baselines on 15 out of 17 real-world datasets.

Efficient Representation Learning of Subgraphs by Subgraph-To-Node Translation
correspondingData: The paper "S2N Translation for Generative Neural Networks" demonstrates that the S2N translation reduces memory and computational costs in the model training and inference by constructing a new coarse graph that summarizes the original subgraph into a node. This approach can potentially be beneficial for GNN practitioners as it allows for more efficient model training and inference.

title: Feature Unlearning for Generative Models via Implicit Feedback
Feature Unlearning for Generative Models via Implicit Feedback
correspondingData: The implicit feedback mechanism identifies which features to unlearn from the generated model by allowing users to select images that contain the target feature. Based on the feedback, a dataset with positive and negative examples is constructed. The positive and negative examples are then used to unlearn the model. However, it's important to note that the positive examples can have features other than the target feature, hence the implicit feedback.

title: Denoising MCMC for Accelerating Diffusion-Based Generative Models
correspondingData: Current diffusion methods, such as MCMC methods, often have difficulty crossing low-density regions in high-dimensional multimodal distributions. For Langevin dynamics, at a low-density region, the score function vanishes, resulting in a meaningless diffusion. Moreover, natural data often lies on a low-dimensional manifold. Thus, once Langevin dynamics leaves the data manifold, it becomes impossible for Langevin dynamics to find its way back.

correspondingData: The complexity-gap score is a training-free data valuation score that quantifies the influence of individual instances in generalization of two-layer overparameterized neural networks. It reduces the computational cost significantly compared to dealing with previously generalized deep learning models, as it does not require actual training of a model, which often demands high computational cost.
